@node "Files" "File types"
SeqGen generates three types of files: sequence, amino acid and settings
files. Here is some information about them.


@{u}1. Sequence file@{uu}

This file contains the sequence saved through @{"Project/Save" link "0.4" 0} menu item. The file
contains also format settings and the name of amino acid table used when Save
item was chosen. File name has normally postfix ".seq", for example,
"ß-galactosidase.seq".


@{u}2. Amino acid file@{uu}

This is a list of short and respective long symbols of @{"amino acids" link "Amino acids" 0}. In the
SeqGen archive the file "NormalAcids.aa" contains the 20 amino acids found in
natural proteins. File name has normally postfix ".aa". When @{"started" link "Start" 0}, SeqGen
tries to load file "config/Normalacids.aa", where "config" directory lies in
the program directory.


@{u}3. Settings file@{uu}

This file contains information about your @{"editing settings" link "3.1" 0}, @{"format settings" link "3.2" 0}
and window size and position preferences. File name has normally postfix
".prefs". When @{"started" link "Start" 0}, SeqGen tries to load file "config/SeqGen.prefs", where
config directory lies in the program directory. Window settings are loaded
only when starting SeqGen.
@endnode

@node "Antibody" "Antibodies"
Antibodies are B-lymphocyte-derived small proteins, which are synthetized
against and bind to the causative agent of infection (bacterium, virus,
fungus). By binding they help other parts of the immune system to destroy the
microbe.

Secondary antibodies are antibodies against other antibodies (!), which are
made for laboratory use. They can be coupled with some marker, for example a
colour-producing enzyme, and used to detect human antibodies.
@endnode

